Using Bayesian Logistic Regression to Predict Outcomes of Denver Nuggets Games

Cameron Stivers

2023-03-13

Research Topic

In this report, I will be doing a Bayesian logistic regression analysis predicting the outcome of games played by the Denver Nuggets, a team in the NBA. In particular, the predictor variables that I will be looking at are whether the game is played at home or away, whether the opponent is from the Western or Eastern Conference, the opponents current win percentage, and their net points per game (the difference between points scored and points given up per game).

Setting Priors

In this model, there are 5 parameters of interest: 4 for each of the predictors, and the last being the intercept (beta0) of the model, which in this context is the log(odds) of a Nuggets win in a game where the other parameters are set to 0, so a home game against a Western Conference opponent with a win percentage and net points per game of 0. The other parameters represent the increase in the log(odds) of a Nuggets win when their respective predictor increases by 1, while controlling for the other predictors. In the case of the home/away and West/East variables, this would be interpreted as the change in log(odds) of a Nuggets win if we switched from an away game to a home game, or from a Western opponent to an Eastern opponent.

beta1: Home/away beta2: Opponent Conference beta3: Opp. Win Percent beta4: Opp. Net Points Per Game (Points Per Game - Points Given Up Per Game)

My criteria for the prior distributions were somewhat loose. Each of them follow a normal distribution. For \(\beta_0\), my knowledge of the recent Denver Nuggets teams tells me that in an average game, they should have a more than 50% chance of victory, given that theyve consistently been a playoff team over the last few years. I chose an average of about 60%, which would lead to a log(odds) of about 0.4, which I raised to 0.6 in my prior distribution to account for opposing teams almost certainly having a win percentage above 0, and thus decreasing (according to my prior belief) the chance of victory. For the others, I chose mostly positive values for \(\beta_1\), as I believe being the home team does raise a teams chance of victory, but not by much. For \(\beta_2\), I dont believe the conference of the opponent has much of an effect on the chance of victory, and I am also uncertain about what the direction of influence would be, so I centered it at 0. \(\beta_3\) and \(\beta_4\) are each mostly negative because I expect stronger opponents to reduce the chance of victory for the Nuggets. Small adjustments were made until I reached a satisfying prior predictive distribution.

# Prior distributions and predictions after tuning
n_reps = 10000

beta0 = rnorm(n_reps, 0.6, 0.1)

beta1 = rnorm(n_reps, 0.08, 0.04)

beta2 = rnorm(n_reps, 0, 0.05)

beta3 = rnorm(n_reps, -0.5, 0.2)

beta4 = rnorm(n_reps, -0.1, 0.04)

x1 = rbinom(n_reps, 1, 0.5) # simulating if a game is at home
x2 = rbinom(n_reps, 1, 30 / 82) # simulating whether a game is played against an eastern opponent
x3 = rnorm(n_reps, 0.5, 0.12) # simulating opponent win percentages
x4 = rnorm(n_reps, 0, 3) # simulating  opponent net points per game

y = (exp(beta0 + beta1*x1 + beta2*x2 + beta3*x3 + beta4*x4)) / (1 + exp(beta0 + beta1*x1 + beta2*x2 + beta3*x3 + beta4*x4))

outcome = rbinom(n_reps, 1, y)

prior = data.frame(beta0, beta1, beta2, beta3, beta4, x1, x2, x3, x4, y, outcome)
hist(prior$y, xlab = "Percent Chance of Win", main = "Prior Predictive Probability of the Nuggets Winning")

# Simulating win proportions in 100 game samples
win_prop = c()
for (n in 1:100){
  total_wins = 0
  for (m in (1+(100*(n-1))):(100*n)){
    total_wins = outcome[m] + total_wins
  }
  win_prop[n] = total_wins / 100
}
hist(win_prop, xlab = "Proportion of Games Won", main = "Prior Predictive Distribution of Proportion of Games Won")

The Data

The data below is sourced from basketball-reference.com. The sample used is Denver Nuggets games over the past 2 seasons (150 games in total, playoffs not included). Because the sample is from the last 2 seasons, it safely represents the population of Nuggets regular season games, as all teams in the NBA are represented more than once in both home and away games.

nuggets_scores <- read.table("nuggetsgames.csv", sep = ",", header = TRUE, fileEncoding = "UTF-8-BOM")

In Nuggets wins, a slightly larger proportion of their opponents win percentages are low than in losses, which makes sense because we expect more wins to come against teams that have lost more often. Where this pattern is more evident is in the opponents net points per game, as there is a clear shift in the distribution of opponent net points per game between wins and losses. In wins, more opposing teams have a negative net points per game, and in losses, more teams have a positive net points per game, which also makes sense because net points per game is indicative of the opponents strength.

Posterior

Setting the priors that were determined earlier:

prior_intercept <- set_prior("normal(0.4,0.1)", class = "Intercept")
prior1 <- set_prior("normal(0.08,0.04)", class = "b", coef = "Home")
prior2 <- set_prior("normal(0,0.05)", class = "b", coef = "Oconference")
prior3 <- set_prior("normal(-0.5,0.2)", class = "b", coef = "OppWP")
prior4 <- set_prior("normal(-0.1,0.04)", class = "b", coef = "ONetPPG")

Fitting the logistic regression model using these prior distributions:

fit <- brm(data = nuggets_scores,
           family = bernoulli(),
           Result ~ Home + Oconference + OppWP + ONetPPG,
           prior = c(prior_intercept,prior1,prior2,prior3,prior4),
           iter = 3500,
           warmup = 1000,
           chains = 4,
           refresh = 0)
## Compiling Stan program...
## Start sampling

A lot of the parameters look uninformative and have a lot of uncertainty, shown by their large spread, specifically the intercept. There is strong correlation between the intercept and win percentage, which makes sense because a win percentage must always be at least 0, so a change in the intercept is correlated with a change in \(\beta_3\). Centering \(\beta_3\), along with \(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_2\) should get rid of any correlation with the intercept.

nuggets_scores <- nuggets_scores |>
  mutate(OppWP = OppWP - mean(OppWP)) |>
  mutate(Home = Home - 0.5) |>
  mutate(Oconference = Oconference - 0.5)

After observing data, in an average Nuggets game (note that we say average now that \(\beta_1\), \(\beta_2\) and \(\beta_3\) are centered), there is an 80% chance that the log(odds) of a Nuggets victory is between 0.299 and 0.522, or the odds of a Nuggets victory is between 1.349 and 1.685. There is an 80% chance that the difference in the log(odds) of victory between a home Nuggets game and an away game is between 0.035 and 0.137, or the odds of a Nuggets win are between 1.036 and 1.147 times higher at home. There is an 80% chance that the log(odds) of a Nuggets win against an Eastern opponent are between -0.063 and 0.065 higher than against a Western opponent, or the odds of a Nuggets win against an Eastern opponent are between 0.939 and 1.067 times higher than against a Western opponent. There is an 80% chance that the each increase of 0.1 in opponent win percentage decreases the log(odds) of a Nuggets win by between 0.022 and 0.073, or the odds are multiplied by between 1.022 and 1.076. There is an 80% chance that each increase of 1 in the opponents net points per game decreases the log(odds) of a Nuggets win by between 0.085 and 0.120, or for each increase of 1 in opponent net points per game, the odds of a Nuggets win are multiplied by between 0.863 and 0.929.

n_rep = length(posterior$b_Intercept)

Some general conclusions: In most games, the Nuggets are more likely to win than than lose based on the posterior distribution, with a mean chance of victory of about 61.1%. Being the home team only barely increases their chance of victory (the interval only goes up by about 1 percent). Whether the opponent is from the East or West has basically no influence on the Nuggets odds of winning the game. Surprisingly, the opponents record has hardly any influence, but in hindsight, it makes some sense because early in the season, a lot of teams have either a perfect record or a winless record. The biggest influence on their chance of victory is the net points per game of their opponent. These results are mostly expected and make sense, as the Nuggets were a playoff team last season and are on track to be the top Western Conference team this year, so it should be expected that they have a higher chance of victory in most games, and that their chances are lower if the opposing team is stronger than others.

pp_check(fit, ndraws = 100)

The posterior predictive check suggests that we have a suitable model.

What if BRMS Chooses the Priors?

fit_noprior <- brm(data = nuggets_scores,
           family = bernoulli(),
           Result ~ Home + Oconference + OppWP + ONetPPG,
           iter = 3500,
           warmup = 1000,
           chains = 4,
           refresh = 0)
## Compiling Stan program...
## Start sampling
plot(fit_noprior)

Noticeably, the posterior distributions when prior distributions are not given suggest more uncertainty, given that the spread is larger for each of them. This implies that the posterior distribution is noticeably sensitive to the prior distributions that we come up with. Also, we still see that opponent net points per game is still influential to win chance, as the distribution above suggests with a lot of certainty that the relationship is negative. With a variable like home or away, we can see that the previous model was likely influenced by the prior belief that being the home team has little, but a positive, influence on win chance, but here, it is evident that there is less certainty on how strong that influence is, despite it showing a positive one.

Should there have been more data, these distributions would likely have shown more certainty and less spread, but the trade-off of that is once we start adding more games from years past, we start to include games from versions of the Nuggets that become less and less similar to the current team. Since we are concerned about the chance of the team winning future games, it is best to use data that is most relevant to the current team, which means the prior distributions we use are influential to the posterior distributions and are very important to consider beforehand.

Frequentist Analysis

The code below was used from: https://www.r-bloggers.com/2015/09/how-to-perform-a-logistic-regression-in-r/

freq_model <- glm(formula = Result ~ Home + Oconference + OppWP + ONetPPG, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = nuggets_scores)
summary(freq_model)

The results from the frequentist analysis show that \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_4\) are statistically significant (assuming an \(\alpha\) of 0.05). \(\beta_1\), \(\beta_2\), and \(\beta_3\) are all not statistically significant, meaning there is not enough evidence that being the home or away team, the conference of the opponent, and the opponents win percentage are associated with the Nuggets chance of winning the game. These are consistent with the Bayesian analysis, as we only saw opponent net points per game have any noticeable effect on the posterior predictive distribution when controlling for the other variables.
